et: borrowed from French, borrowed from a Tupi word recorded as {it}unaü{/it} in the 17th century

The use of the word {it}unau{/it} as a generic name for the two-toed sloth (and {it}ai{/it} as a name for the three-toed sloth) is owed to Georges-Louis Leclerc de {et_link|buffon|Buffon:b}, who so denominated them in {it}Histoire naturelle, générale et particulière,{/it} tome treizième (Paris, 1765), p. 34 ff. The word {it}ai{/it} is well-documented (see note at {et_link|ai|ai}), but {it}unau{/it} is apparently reported only in a description of the sloth by the French Capuchin priest Claude d'Abbeville, who resided on the island of Maranhão (French {it}Maragnan,{/it} now called in Portuguese {it}ilha de São Luís{/it} or {it}Upaon-Açu{/it}) in 1612-15: "Il y en a de deux sortes, aucuns sonts grands enuiron comme les Lieures qu'ils appellent {it}Vnaü,{/it} & les autres sont deux fois presque plus grands qu'ils appellent {it}Vnaü Oaüssou{/it} & d'autant plus monstrueux" ({it}Histoire de la mission des pères capucins en l'Isle de Maragnan et terres circonvoisines,{/it} Paris, 1614, p. 252). ("There are two kinds of them [sloths], some are about as large as hares, which they call {it}unaü,{/it} and others are almost two times as large, which they call {it}unaü oaüssou,{/it} and all the more monstrous.") Though the suffixed word {it}oaüssou{/it} [wasu] means "large" in Tupi, and a number of other names cited by d'Abbeville are familiar from other records, {it}unaü{/it} does not appear to be attested elsewhere.
shortdef: two-toed sloth

pt: {it}Disinterested{/it} and {it}uninterested{/it} have a tangled history. {it}Uninterested{/it} originally meant impartial, but this sense fell into disuse during the 18th century. About the same time the original sense of {it}disinterested{/it} also disappeared, with {it}uninterested{/it} developing a new sense—the present meaning—to take its place. The original sense of {it}uninterested{/it} is still out of use, but the original sense of {it}disinterested{/it} revived in the early 20th century. The revival has since been under frequent attack as an illiteracy and a blurring or loss of a useful distinction. Actual usage shows otherwise. The "free from selfish interest" sense of {it}disinterested{/it} is still its most frequent sense, especially in edited prose; it shows no sign of vanishing. Further, {it}disinterested{/it} has developed an additional sense—"no longer interested"—perhaps influenced by the "deprive of" sense of the prefix {it}dis-{/it}, that contrasts with {it}uninterested{/it}.

usages.pl: Can something be very {parahw}unique{/parahw} or somewhat unique?
pt: Many commentators have objected to the comparison or modification (as by {it}somewhat{/it} or {it}very{/it}) of {it}unique{/it}, often asserting that a thing is either unique or it is not. Objections are based chiefly on the assumption that {it}unique{/it} has but a single absolute sense, an assumption contradicted by information readily available in a dictionary. {it}Unique{/it} dates back to the 17th century but was little used until the end of the 18th when, according to the Oxford English Dictionary, it was reacquired from French. H. J. Todd entered it as a foreign word in his edition (1818) of Johnson's Dictionary, characterizing it as "affected and useless." Around the middle of the 19th century it ceased to be considered foreign and came into considerable popular use. With popular use came a broadening of application beyond the original two meanings (here numbered senses 1 and 2a). In modern use both comparison and modification are widespread and standard but are confined to the extended senses 2b and 3. When sense 1 or sense 2a is intended, {it}unique{/it} is used without qualifying modifiers.

quotes.t: There are no clear blueprints to be discovered in history that can help us shape the future as we wish. Each historical event is a {qword}unique{/qword} congeries of factors, people, or chronology.
[Tiger] Wood's {qword}unique{/qword} skill set was on display again at last week's U.S. Open, but this victory was more visceral. It was all heart.
Space is a strange and {qword}unique{/qword} item—you can't take it to a lab and analyze it like beef jerky.

A century ago a doctor was considered to be part of a social elite. He—and medicine was then very much a masculine endeavor—had a {qword}unique{/qword} mastery of a special body of knowledge. He professed a commitment to levels of competence and integrity that he expected society to respect and trust.

Most stars are not born in isolation but instead in groups of several thousand to tens of thousands, all of which emerge from the same parent cloud of gas. Each cloud has a {qword}unique{/qword} and homogeneous mix of chemical elements and isotopes, which its stellar progeny inherits. Even when the stars disperse, they retain their {qword}unique{/qword} chemical tag …
As a dozen new books will testify, our nation is in the midst of a great barbecue renaissance, with each region proudly claiming its own {qword}unique{/qword} style.

[Tiger] Wood's {qword}unique{/qword} skill set was on display again at last week's U.S. Open, but this victory was more visceral. It was all heart.
Space is a strange and {qword}unique{/qword} item—you can't take it to a lab and analyze it like beef jerky.

A century ago a doctor was considered to be part of a social elite. He—and medicine was then very much a masculine endeavor—had a {qword}unique{/qword} mastery of a special body of knowledge. He professed a commitment to levels of competence and integrity that he expected society to respect and trust.

Most stars are not born in isolation but instead in groups of several thousand to tens of thousands, all of which emerge from the same parent cloud of gas. Each cloud has a {qword}unique{/qword} and homogeneous mix of chemical elements and isotopes, which its stellar progeny inherits. Even when the stars disperse, they retain their {qword}unique{/qword} chemical tag …
As a dozen new books will testify, our nation is in the midst of a great barbecue renaissance, with each region proudly claiming its own {qword}unique{/qword} style.

pt: Many commentators have objected to the comparison or modification (as by {it}somewhat{/it} or {it}very{/it}) of {it}unique{/it}, often asserting that a thing is either unique or it is not. Objections are based chiefly on the assumption that {it}unique{/it} has but a single absolute sense, an assumption contradicted by information readily available in a dictionary. {it}Unique{/it} dates back to the 17th century but was little used until the end of the 18th when, according to the Oxford English Dictionary, it was reacquired from French. H. J. Todd entered it as a foreign word in his edition (1818) of Johnson's Dictionary, characterizing it as "affected and useless." Around the middle of the 19th century it ceased to be considered foreign and came into considerable popular use. With popular use came a broadening of application beyond the original two meanings (here numbered senses 1 and 2a). In modern use both comparison and modification are widespread and standard but are confined to the extended senses 2b and 3. When sense 1 or sense 2a is intended, {it}unique{/it} is used without qualifying modifiers.

quotes.t: … on one occasion, a president (Eisenhower) refers to himself as "conservative." Four years later, the Republican presidential nominee (Goldwater) announces that he is "a conservative." Another sixteen years later, Ronald Reagan, a self-declared conservative, is elected president by an overwhelming majority. By that time—1980—more Americans identify themselves as conservatives than as liberals. This was, and remains, a tectonic transformation, {qword}unprecedented{/qword} in American history.

Fan fiction … was once mainly a fringe pursuit. Now, it's changing the world of fiction, as Internet exposure helps unknown authors find mainstream success. Some Web sites are attracting {qword}unprecedented{/qword} numbers of readers and, in some cases, leading to book deals.

Faced with an {qword}unprecedented{/qword} crisis that combines cyclical turbulence with metastasizing digital technology that steals away revenue and readers at an alarming and seemingly accelerating rate (while offering newspapers only stingy payoffs), publishers and editors everywhere have thrown away their rule books—and, to find their way in this new and alien environment, are ready to implement previously unthinkable changes.

Many of the forces that initially sent the economy into a tailspin in 1929 and 1930 have been at work in the 2000s as well: a stock-market boom turned bust, a real estate boom turned bust, {qword}unprecedented{/qword} levels of consumer debt.
Shakespeare served as exemplar of the writer who achieved success, and an {qword}unprecedented{/qword} degree of financial reward, from his pen alone.

Shocking as it is, more than a month after the hurricane hit, New Orleans is still, for all practical purposes, a ghost town. The entire population has left—an {qword}unprecedented{/qword} situation in modern times in any major city anywhere.

shortdef: having no precedent : novel, unexampled

quotes.t: The Agriculture Department is in an {qword}untenable{/qword} position. With the two hats that it wears—one to protect consumer health and the other to help farmers sell food—it cannot tell us to eat fewer calories. After all, fewer calories generally mean less food, which would fly in the face of the department's mandate to help farmers.

The problem was then resolved—not by finding that the conduct in question was justified, because that would have offended the judge's sense of order, and not by rejecting the applicability of the defense, which would have led to a reportable opinion and an appeal—but through a dismissal of the charges on the wholly {qword}untenable{/qword} ground that the prosecution had not proved its case beyond a reasonable doubt.

But scholars are citizens, too, and if it is wrongheaded to demand political payoff from basic research, it would be equally {qword}untenable{/qword} to demand that research be quarantined from the real-world considerations that weigh so heavily upon us.

All the theories of the Moon's origin proposed before the Apollo Moon landings of 1969 … became {qword}untenable{/qword} when the rocks returned from the Moon proved to be as old as the Earth and significantly dissimilar.

et: Middle English {it}sleve,{/it} going back to Old English {it}slīefe{/it} (West Saxon), {it}slēfe{/it} (Anglian), feminine weak noun, going back to a Germanic noun base {it}*slaubj-{/it} (whence also East Frisian [Saterland] {it}sleeuwe{/it} "sleeve," North Frisian [Mooring] {it}sliiw{/it}), from a verbal root {it}*slaub-{/it} seen also in Old English {it}slēfan{/it} (weak verb) "to slip (clothes) on," Middle Dutch {it}slōven{/it} "to roll up, strip off, slip over something," {it}sloof{/it} "coat of rough cloth, habit," {it}slove{/it} "cover, wrapper," regional German {it}Schlaube{/it} "skin, peel (of fruit, etc.)," going back to Indo-European {it}*slou̯b{sup}h{/sup}-,{/it} causative derivative of {it}*sleu̯b{sup}h{/sup}-{/it} "move easily, slip," whence also Latin (with suffix {it}*-re/o-ko-{/it}) {it}lūbricus{/it} "slippery, difficult to hold"

This Germanic etymon for "sleeve" is evidently of Anglo-Frisian date, judging by its appearance in North and East Frisian; in West Frisian it appears to have been replaced by Dutch {it}mouw.{/it} —The postulation of {it}*slou̯b{sup}h{/sup}-{/it} is based on the R. Lühr's hypothesis (see note at {et_link|slip:5|slip:5}), though others appear to regard {it}*slaub-{/it} as arising within Germanic, without positing an Indo-European base (thus Feist/Lehmann, {it}A Gothic Etymological Dictionary{/it}; G. Kroonen, {it}Etymological Dictionary of Proto-Germanic{/it}); thereby the verb {it}*sleupan-{/it} "to creep, glide" (see {et_link|slip:5|slip:5}) can be added to the above group of words, as well as Gothic {it}afslaupjan{/it} "to strip off (a garment)," a causative with o-grade ablaut. Kroonen additionally cites also Old Frisian {it}slēpan{/it} "to fasten, put (a noose around the neck)" and Old Saxon {it}slōpian{/it} "to loosen." The putative Old English verb {it}slīepan{/it} cited by Feist/Lehmann and Kroonen does not appear to exist, nor does {it}slíefan{/it} cited by Lühr. Kroonen cites as a form comparative within Indo-European Lithuanian {it}įslupti{/it} "to slip in" and Latvian {it}šļupt{/it} "to glide out." For more Germanic nominal derivatives see {et_link|slop:1|slop:1}.

dt: {bc}aspiring to a rank or position higher than one deserves or is entitled to

dt.t: In a seller's market for labor, it seems, there is a danger that the help will get {wi}uppity{/wi}.
… a group of senior male executives referred to my staff of predominantly professional women as {wi}uppity{/wi}.

We talked as long as I dared. She told me to reverse the charges. It was my call, I said. She laughed and said I was getting {wi}uppity{/wi}. I described Mrs. Burgess, how working for her was hardly like being a servant.
Hagar, with child, despised her mistress and flaunted her pregnancy over her. … Sarah flew upon the {wi}uppity{/wi} servant girl and drove her off into the desert.

pt: The adjective {it}uppity{/it} is an informal, somewhat old-fashioned word. When used to mean {ldquo}arrogant{rdquo} or {ldquo}presumptuous,{rdquo} it is no more offensive than either of these synonyms. In its meaning of "aspiring to a rank or position higher than one deserves or is entitled to" it is decidedly disparaging, the implication of the word being that the one described does not deserve or is not entitled to rise in standing. Beyond this denotation, however, {it}uppity{/it} has a long history of being applied to members of racial minorities and especially to Black people. Its association with such uses, and the bigotry they represent, means that when it is used to describe a member of a racial minority it is likely to be considered especially offensive.

shortdef: putting on or marked by airs of superiority : arrogant, presumptuous

{sc}vent{/sc} stresses a strong inner compulsion to express especially in words.
{sc}utter{/sc} implies the use of the voice not necessarily in articulate speech.
{sc}voice{/sc} does not necessarily imply vocal utterance but does imply expression or formulation in words.
{sc}broach{/sc} adds the implication of disclosing for the first time something long thought over or reserved for a suitable occasion.
{sc}air{/sc} implies an exposing or parading of one's views often in order to gain relief or sympathy or attention.
